### Recommendation: Use `TimeProvider` (.NET 8+)

.NET 8 ships `System.TimeProvider` — an abstract class designed exactly for this:

```csharp
public class OrderProcessor(TimeProvider time)
{
    public Order CreateOrder(string id)
    {
        var now = time.GetUtcNow();
        // use `now` instead of DateTime.UtcNow
    }
}
```

In tests, use `Microsoft.Extensions.Time.Testing.FakeTimeProvider`:

```csharp
var fake = new FakeTimeProvider(new DateTimeOffset(2026, 1, 1, 0, 0, 0, TimeSpan.Zero));
var processor = new OrderProcessor(fake);
// assertions are now deterministic
fake.Advance(TimeSpan.FromDays(31)); // simulate expiry
```

In production DI registration:

```csharp
services.AddSingleton(TimeProvider.System);
```

If you're on an older TFM, create a simple `ISystemClock` interface with a `UtcNow` property and inject it the same way. Want me to refactor the code to apply this?
